This code determines if all courses can be finished given prerequisite constraints using DFS-based cycle detection. 
It builds a directed graph where an edge pre[1] → pre[0] indicates the prerequisite must be taken before the course. 
The state array tracks three states for each node: 0 = unvisited, 1 = visiting (currently in recursion stack), and 2 = fully processed (no cycle found). 
For each unvisited course, DFS is performed; if a node in state 1 (back edge) is encountered, a cycle is detected and false is returned. 
Otherwise, the algorithm proceeds and returns true if no cycles are found in the entire graph.

Time Complexity: O(V + E) — each vertex and edge is visited once.
Space Complexity: O(V) — for the recursion stack (up to V depth) and the state array, plus O(V + E) for the adjacency list.

class Solution {
    public boolean canFinish(int numCourses, int[][] prerequisites) {
        List<Integer>[] graph = new ArrayList[numCourses];
        for(int i = 0; i<numCourses; i++){
            graph[i] = new ArrayList<>();
        }
        for(int[] pre : prerequisites) {
            graph[pre[1]].add(pre[0]);
        }

        int[] state = new int[numCourses];
        for(int course = 0; course < numCourses; course++){
            if(!dfs(course, graph, state)){
                return false;
            }
        }
        return true;
    }
    public boolean dfs(int node, List<Integer>[] graph, int[] state){
        if(state[node] == 1){
            return false;
        }
        if(state[node] == 2){
            return true;
        }
        state[node] = 1;
        for(int nbr : graph[node]){
            if(!dfs(nbr, graph, state)){
                return false;
            }
        }
        state[node] = 2;
        return true;
    }
}
